\subsection{Loss-bias check on dropped CRunDec draws}
\label{sec:loss-bias}

Approximately $33\%$ of random-spectrum Model~A draws fail to produce valid CRunDec output for running claims (specifically $3{,}269$ of $10{,}000$ in the baseline run); failures occur when the random spectrum produces pathological QCD configurations (charm-bottom thresholds too close, $\alpha_s$ blow-up, etc.). To check whether this loss biases the reported $p$-values, we compared the distribution of best residuals under surrogate running for the dropped draws against the same distribution for the successful draws.

The two distributions differ. The dropped draws have a median best residual of $8.05 \times 10^{-5}$ versus $5.66 \times 10^{-5}$ for successful draws (ratio $1.42$); a two-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test gives $p_{\text{KS}} \approx 8.5 \times 10^{-26}$. The direction of the bias matters: if dropped draws have \emph{larger} best residuals, then excluding them removes large-residual draws from the null distribution and shifts the retained null toward smaller residuals. Under this shift, the observed residual looks \emph{less} extreme relative to the null than it would if the dropped draws could be included, biasing reported $p$-values upward (i.e., conservatively).

Two caveats on this argument. First, the distributional comparison uses the surrogate running scheme rather than full CRunDec, because the full-CRunDec values are unavailable for the dropped draws by construction. The surrogate did not reproduce full-CRunDec results at the per-draw level (Section~\ref{sec:surrogate-validation}), but aggregate statistics such as medians and KS tests depend on distributional shape rather than on per-draw accuracy, and should therefore be less sensitive to the surrogate's per-draw error. Second, the argument that the reported $p$-values are upper bounds relies on stochastic dominance of the dropped-draw best-residual distribution over the retained-draw distribution. The median shift and KS result support stochastic dominance but do not prove it; a dropped-draw distribution with a heavier left tail than its median would suggest is not ruled out by these summary statistics. We therefore report the Model~A $p$-values in Table~\ref{tab:pvalues} as upper bounds \emph{under the stochastic-dominance assumption supported by the median and KS evidence}, rather than as unconditional upper bounds. The qualitative ranking is unaffected by this bias since it acts uniformly across claims.


