\subsection{Temporal convergence as an additional discriminator}
\label{sec:temporal}

Statistical tests against null models and central-value drift thresholds both speak to present-day significance. A third discriminator, available without any new theory, is whether the residual $|Q - 2/3|$ converges toward zero as measurement precision improves over time. A relation that is exact in nature should produce a residual that shrinks as the propagated $\sigma_Q$ shrinks; a relation that is a coincidence at a particular epoch should produce a residual that remains pinned at its accidental value while $\sigma_Q$ decreases past it.

The original lepton Koide relation is the textbook example. When Koide proposed $Q = 2/3$ in 1981--1983, the world-average $m_\tau$ was $1784.2 \pm 3.2$~MeV, while the value required by the formula given $m_e$ and $m_\mu$ was $1776.97$~MeV. BES measurements published in 1992 and 1996 converged to $1776.96 \pm 0.31$~MeV, and subsequent refinements have remained within $\sim 1\sigma$ of the same value (PDG~2024: $1776.86 \pm 0.12$~MeV). The residual $|Q - 2/3|$ has tracked the shrinking $m_\tau$ uncertainty downward across four decades.

By contrast, the Rivero and Cao quark-side claims that survive Model~A do not show the same pattern. The Rivero $(s, c, b)$ residual at self-scales has remained in the range $|Q - 2/3| \approx 7.5$--$8.2 \times 10^{-3}$ since the FLAG~2013 update introduced $N_f = 2 + 1 + 1$ averages: across FLAG~2013, 2016, 2019, 2021, and~2024 the residual has not budged outside that band while the propagated $\sigma_Q$ has shrunk by roughly a factor of three to its present value of $\sim 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$. The Cao $(c, b, t)$ self-scale residual has shown a similar stability, sitting near $3.5$--$4.7 \times 10^{-3}$ across the same period (slightly increasing as $m_t$ has been refined). In both cases, the ratio of the residual to the propagated $\sigma_Q$ is currently of order $9$--$14$.

