Compare two independent reviews of the same manuscript.

REVIEW A:
{
  "verdict": "flagged",
  "confidence": 0.89,
  "reasoning": "The manuscript is careful in many places and unusually transparent about implementation problems, but several methodological choices materially limit or potentially invalidate the strength of its central claims. The most important concerns are: (i) the principal null model (Model A) is ad hoc and not clearly aligned with the inferential target, yet it is used to support substantive ranking claims about prior literature; (ii) one-third of Model A simulations fail, and the argument that this only makes p-values conservative is not demonstrated from the actual statistic under the actual engine; (iii) the look-elsewhere accounting appears incomplete because the search space is defined after seeing the literature/current data and excludes obvious analyst degrees of freedom while still drawing inferential conclusions; and (iv) Monte Carlo resolution is limited for reported small p-values. These issues do not clearly force retraction because the headline full-search conclusion under both nulls is qualitative and plausibly still true, but they do require major revision before strong methodological claims can be accepted.",
  "findings": [
    {
      "finding": "Model A uses an arbitrary random-spectrum prior (log-uniform masses over analyst-chosen endpoints, then sorted and assigned to quark slots) that is not clearly justified as the correct null for the question of whether quark Koide relations are surprising.",
      "severity": "MAJOR-REVISION",
      "justification": "This is the main source of the small p-values used to rank single-triple claims. If the null does not correspond to a scientifically meaningful reference ensemble, those p-values are not interpretable as evidence strength. The paper acknowledges arbitrariness, but still draws substantive conclusions from Model A. If confirmed, this would require revision of the inferential framing and likely temper conclusions, though it does not necessarily invalidate the descriptive full-search result."
    },
    {
      "finding": "Approximately 33% of Model A pseudo-experiments are dropped due to CRunDec failure, yet the paper treats the resulting p-values as conservative upper bounds based only on surrogate-running summaries rather than the actual statistic under the actual full-CRunDec implementation.",
      "severity": "MAJOR-REVISION",
      "justification": "A missing-not-at-random simulation fraction this large can materially distort tail probabilities. The manuscript does not establish stochastic dominance for the full statistic, and explicitly admits it cannot. Therefore the claim that reported p-values are conservative is not demonstrated. If confirmed, the Model A p-values and ranking may shift enough to change conclusions about which claims 'survive' Model A."
    },
    {
      "finding": "The look-elsewhere correction is only partial but is used in places as if it were a broad accounting of multiplicity; important analyst degrees of freedom are excluded by construction (target value fixed at 2/3, scheme fixed, discrete scale set chosen from 'physically interpretable' options, top quark fixed at self-scale, no continuous scales).",
      "severity": "MAJOR-REVISION",
      "justification": "The paper does state that the audit is non-exhaustive, but then uses the resulting p-values to characterize claims as surviving or not surviving the look-elsewhere burden. Because the search space was itself analyst-defined after the literature/current data landscape existed, omitted flexibility could substantially weaken significance claims. This does not invalidate the descriptive computations on the chosen search set, but it does overstate inferential finality."
    },
    {
      "finding": "The definition of the trial family is not fully pre-specified and appears partially tailored to existing claims and current data, undermining the interpretation of multiplicity-corrected p-values as confirmatory even for 'prior' claims.",
      "severity": "MAJOR-REVISION",
      "justification": "The manuscript concedes that the author's prior (c,b,t) claim was formulated on the same central values and that the present audit was built afterward. More broadly, the enumerated scale list and claim families are literature-driven and audited post hoc. If confirmed, these p-values are exploratory/descriptive rather than strong confirmatory evidence. Revision is needed to tighten language and avoid overclaiming."
    },
    {
      "finding": "Monte Carlo precision is weak for the smallest reported Model A p-values, with only 10,000 simulations used to report p = 0.002.",
      "severity": "MAJOR-REVISION",
      "justification": "A p-value of 0.002 from 10,000 replicates corresponds to about 20 tail events, making the estimate sensitive to simulation noise and implementation details, especially given the 33% simulation failure issue and multiple robustness variants. This may not reverse the qualitative statement that the p-value is small under that null, but exact rankings and thresholded statements like 'meets p<0.05' are unstable enough to require more simulation."
    },
    {
      "finding": "The bootstrap null (Model B) treats quoted FLAG/PDG uncertainties as Gaussian measurement noise on a six-parameter mass vector and perturbs all masses jointly, but this does not represent the full epistemic structure of these averages, scheme conversions, and shared lattice/systematic inputs.",
      "severity": "MINOR",
      "justification": "This is a simplification common in practice, and the manuscript does attempt correlation sensitivity analyses. It mainly affects the exact interpretation of Model B tail probabilities, not the broad conclusion that most closures are within current uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "finding": "The paper mixes trial-level thresholds using triple-specific sigma_Q with a 'representative' sigma_Q in narrative summaries, which risks confusion about what statistic is actually being counted.",
      "severity": "MINOR",
      "justification": "This is mostly a reporting clarity issue. The manuscript says per-triple values are used in computation, but the presentation could mislead readers. It is unlikely to change the principal conclusions if clarified."
    },
    {
      "finding": "The use of empirical hit counts such as '|Q-2/3| < sigma_Q' as descriptive evidence is somewhat arbitrary and secondary to the best-residual statistic, but the manuscript does not fully justify why these summaries are informative.",
      "severity": "MINOR",
      "justification": "This does not appear central to the main conclusions because the formal p-values use simulation, but the threshold choice is conventional rather than principled and should be clearly framed as descriptive."
    },
    {
      "finding": "The temporal-convergence section is not a valid independent statistical discriminator in the form presented, because it uses post hoc historical trajectories without a formal model for expected drift under null and alternative hypotheses.",
      "severity": "MINOR",
      "justification": "As presented, this is heuristic rather than inferential. It should not be used as a strong methodological support for conclusions, but it is supplementary and does not drive the main result."
    },
    {
      "finding": "No adjustment is made for Monte Carlo uncertainty when comparing nearby p-values across robustness variants or claim rankings, yet the discussion sometimes interprets small differences substantively.",
      "severity": "MINOR",
      "justification": "Given the limited simulation counts, some differences across variants may be within Monte Carlo noise. This is a reporting/interpretation issue rather than a fatal flaw."
    }
  ]
}

